<br>
It's not the class I picked when I made a mage.  I picked a mage to do nice damage, but still maintain some flexibility.<br>
<br>
The reason I like it at all is because it's overpowered.  A mage making rods means that mana values mean nothing.  No one needs any sort of individual mana regen and there is no more limitation on the number of spells each person on a raid can cast.<br>
<br>
I never asked to be needed.  I just asked to be a magician.  Thats why I picked a magician.  And no, rods dont even fit the mage class; you can't just slap an effect on a summoned item and all of a sudden it fits for the mage class...if that worked, that would mean I should get a summoned rod of torpor or a summoned rod of manaburn.<br>
<br>
I make lots of rods because that is what it takes to win.  I don't enjoy tough raid encounters because it means I am making a ton of rods instead of doing damage.  I expect everyone in my guild to do what it takes to win, and they expect the same from me.  Rods are what it takes to win. <p><img src="http://www.lehigh.edu/~dsf3/EQ/rhionsligo.jpg" align="center"><br>
