<br>
I picked mage because I liked seeing little gnomes everywhere with huge mudballs trailing behind.<br>
<br>
While the summoning portion really applied to pets during the first release, CoTH added an extra a 4rd dimension, and I found it appealing that we had such a unique spell.  I love direct damage too, but I do know that I will always take a backseat to Wizards in that field. <br>
<br>
Unlike some other mages, I use my pet on raids.  I'm very watchful of my surroundings due to my earlier levels and find myself in external camra almost all the time.  <br>
<br>
I make it a point to NOT let myself reduce myself into a &quot;mod rod whore&quot;.  The time needed to balance summoning, pets, damage shields, DD's and anything else is above and beyond more time consuming and difficult than <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>any</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> other class I've played for the last 3.5 years.<br>
<br>
It's also more worthwhile, and it's rewarding to me.<br>
<br>
<br>
However, the role isn't perfect. I don't often summon rods until a major encounter, or when a critical situation appears, or in a smaller event: a death.  Even then, I rarely get tells from clerics who need mana.  In all other circumstances: if you want mana, then sit down and med up.<br>
<br>
<br>
I feel a large part of the mage problems with mod rods comes from guilds that only see classes on their face value, and ignore the person behind the screen. I've said this before: The T-rod is not the ungodly enforcer of Verant HQ logic.  It's a spell, and you have a choice to summon it for whatever reasons.  If your guild leaders and members yell, swear and belittle you for not doing your &quot;job&quot; full time 24/7, the problem is with the guild - <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  not</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> the mage class as a whole but with the thinking and shortsidedness of those that run the guild.<br>
<br>
<br>
